:name: NavHAL F401RE test runner
:description: Boots a Renode STM32F4 machine model, loads the navtest ELF,
:             routes USART2 to a log file, and runs the suite to completion.
:
:             Variables (set by the caller via the Monitor before `include`):
:               $bin     — absolute path to the test ELF
:               $logfile — absolute path for the captured UART log
:
:             tools/renode/run_tests.sh wires these up with:
:               renode --console --disable-xwt \
:                 -e "$bin = @<elf>; $logfile = @<log>; i @<this-file>"

using sysbus

# The Nucleo-F401RE shares its silicon family with the STM32F4 Discovery
# board; Renode ships a mainline `stm32f4_discovery` platform model that
# exposes the same USART2/GPIO/timer set used by the navtest binary.
mach create "navhal"
machine LoadPlatformDescription @platforms/boards/stm32f4_discovery.repl

# Silence Cortex-M private-peripheral warnings. The `stm32f4_discovery`
# Renode model omits the DWT block (0xE0001000–0xE0001FFF — read by every
# `hal_cycle_counter_get`) and the ITM/TPIU/ETM cluster at 0xE0000000.
# Without these silenced, the cycle-counter tests flood the log with
# "ReadDoubleWord from non existing peripheral at 0xE0001004" once per
# iteration. The cycle-counter suite is a HIL-only test in practice
# (see docs/testing/findings.md §4); silencing the range keeps the
# Renode log readable without changing test outcomes.
sysbus SilenceRange <0xE0000000, 0xE0001FFF>

# Silence model-tag warnings on peripherals that Renode does model but
# tags certain bits as "known but not implemented." These bits *are*
# correctly written by the firmware — Renode just doesn't simulate
# their secondary effects. The warnings would otherwise flood the log
# once per write. Suppressing at level 3 (error-only) for these
# peripherals keeps real errors visible but drops the noise.
logLevel 3 gpioPortC
logLevel 3 rcc
logLevel 3 timer1
logLevel 3 timer2
logLevel 3 timer3
logLevel 3 timer4
logLevel 3 dma1
logLevel 3 dma2
logLevel 3 nvic

# Send USART2 traffic to the log file; CI greps the file for the navtest
# summary. `flushAfterWrite` keeps the log usable even if the emulation
# is killed mid-run.
sysbus.usart2 CreateFileBackend $logfile true

sysbus LoadELF $bin

# Renode is slow per emulated second when the firmware busy-waits — and
# our clock-init paths busy-wait on PLL/HSE ready flags that the Renode
# RCC model doesn't always assert promptly. Empirically the full 142-test
# suite consumes ~90 minutes wall-clock on this rig; 3 emulated hours is
# a comfortable cap that finishes well inside that.
#
# This RunFor is the *hang backstop*, not the success-path exit. The
# firmware enters an idle loop after the last test, so it never naturally
# stops — and `RunFor` would otherwise keep emulating those NOPs for the
# full 3 emulated hours. tools/renode/run_tests.sh watches the UART log
# and SIGTERMs Renode the moment "Total failures:" appears, so the budget
# only matters when the suite genuinely hangs.
#
# `emulation RunFor` starts emulation itself — do NOT pair it with a
# separate `start` line (Renode 1.16 errors with "This action is not
# available when emulation is already started").
emulation RunFor "03:00:00"
quit
